<br>
The <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://eqcleric.gameglow.com/forums/showthread.php?s=&amp;threadid=15364&amp;highlight=Chain" target="top">Cleric's Forum</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> has a good thread explaining CHeal Rotations beginning with this post:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Basic healing techniques <br>
------------------------ <br>
<br>
&quot;Heal your group&quot; - yep it's what we learned in Crushbone, no explanation needed. <br>
<br>
Assist healing - well known and very effective.. make an /assist key, target the mob, /assist. Rinse and repeat. <br>
<br>
CH chain - aggro is focused on one tank, clerics cast CH in a set rotation. The meat and potatoes of high level raids. <br>
<br>
The &quot;DL spam&quot; - aggro is focused on one tank, clerics spam-cast DL as needed. Sloppy but sometimes effective. <br>
<br>
<br>
Multiple target fights <br>
---------------------- <br>
<br>
Good examples of these fights: ToV farming, NToV clearing, Ssra clearing, ring encounters. <br>
<br>
Best group configurations have 1 cleric and one secondary healer (druids and pallies are great for this role). Pretty much it's assumed that you're covering your group 1st and foremost, then tossing in some assist healing to help out your fellow clerics. The secondary healer is your best friend here. <br>
<br>
The real fundamental law in higher end dungeons - never let tanks drop below 2 bubbles of health. Watching 3 drakes tear a tank to shreds in 2 secs is not a pretty sight. And it usually has a chain effect (once that tank that you've been healing is dead, good chance one of the mobs is comin' for you next). Just forget all you learned about CH efficiency in Sebilis.. it doesn't matter. If you're not casting CH when the tank is at 3 bub of health you're running a risk of it landing too late. <br>
<br>
Also make sure to call your heals in /say with macros.. this is a great way for your other clerics to know what you're doing and vice versa. Yea it creates some spam but it's well worth it. <br>
<br>
Main-tank fights (aka the CH chain) <br>
----------------------------------- <br>
<br>
Good examples: Vindi/Statue/Tormax, NToV dragons, etc etc etc <br>
<br>
Group configuration here really is unimportant, there are only 3 important pieces of information you need: <br>
<br>
1) Cleric chain order <br>
2) Chain pause(s) <br>
3) Main tank order <br>
<br>
Chains are usually done via a macro similar to this: <br>
/cast 3 <br>
/pause 26 <br>
/2 [1] CH INC ON %t ---- GO NextClericPerson <br>
<br>
The /cast line # will be dependent on where your CH is of course. The message line assumes you are /join'ed into the appropriate healing chat channel being used for the raid. The [1] at the beginning represents your position in the chain.. this helps as it's sometimes hard to remember who's in what position in the chain, with numbers if someone LD's, basic math skills that I assume we all have come into play. <br>
<br>
The most important responsibility you have in a CH chain is to cast a CH when your time comes.. get a feel for the timing of the pause, this will help you greatly if the cleric prior to you is lagging or goes LD. There is nothing more catastrophic than if you wait for a GO message that never comes. <br>
<br>
Minor MT fights (aka the DL spam) <br>
--------------------------------- <br>
<br>
Good examples: ST stuff, Kland/Sont <br>
<br>
On some targets, DPS isn't high enough to justify a full CH chain (or there are aggro issues with CH). In these cases, if the fight is short, the chaotic DL spam method is easy and effective. After all the game isn't giving out style points... <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Final thoughts <br>
-------------- <br>
<br>
The most important facet IMO to playing a cleric is just the teamwork. No matter how we're doing the healing for a given raid, either we all do well or we all fail. One cleric can't save the day, there are no heroes. The best thing we can do is just work well w/ the other clerics in keeping everyone alive. <br>
<br>
Also when Im not doing a CH chain I always have a fizzle protection script that i use for all my heals, Im sure you guys do to but just in case someone doesn't here it is =) <br>
<br>
/pause 5,/cast # <br>
/cast # <br>
/g CH %t <br>
/say CH %t <br>
<br>
<br>
Can be used with all healing spells its really nice to if you happen to fizzle it will autostart another heal right when it needs to without you having to have your mouse cursor on the spell gem. <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Some more scattered CH chain thoughts... <br>
<br>
Being the 1st cleric in the chain - the only real important thing you need to do is anticipate the pull. This can be difficult esp. on AE'ing mobs where we are parked staring at a wall. The key thing to remember is that if you don't have CH going BEFORE the MT engages, the MT is dead w/o assist heals. Ideally you need to anticipate about 5-8 secs prior to MT engagement. <br>
<br>
For AE'ing mobs, get close to the corner where the MT will be receiving the mob, and switch to your 3rd person views so you can see the pull come in. If the pulling monk comes into view, this is probably a good moment to start the chain. If the mob comes into view, this is definitely a good moment to start . <br>
<br>
For non-AE mobs, just set yourself up somewhere where you can both see the incoming mob, and stay in CH range of the MT (both where he'll initially engage the mob, and also where he might plan to move the mob back to). <br>
<br>
-------------------- <br>
<br>
Depending on the speed of the chain, clerics towards the end of the chain should be ready to throw 1 or 2 assist heals right at the initial point of engagement. In a 4 cleric chain at pause 26 (~4-5 sec delay chain), the 4th cleric can toss a DL and still have time before their rotation spot. This can often make the difference if the 1st cleric is a little slow starting, or has trouble anticipating the pull. Quicker chains usually will have more clerics, so in these cases the 6/7/8 spots will take on this responsibility. <br>
<br>
Once the chain starts, however, it's best if you stop any assist healing unless you are confident that your mana pool can hold up, or unless the encounter requires it (Nevederia for instance). Usually if chain clerics are expected to heal non-MT personnel, this will be announced explicitly <br>
<br>
Ok Ive also incorporated a fizzle proof macro for the chain...this will increase the delay on the /pause 26 so lowering it to /pause 21 or even 20 because of latency I think it will work just fine. <br>
<br>
/sit off <br>
/pause 5,/cast 4 <br>
/cast 4 <br>
/pause 20 <br>
/2 CH INC %t ---- GO NEXT CLERIC<br>
<br>
Feel Free to sticky it <br>
<br>
